38-5. A-SEC-5: Trust placement: JWT claims used only after signature verification, CORS never the access control, client identity headers never trusted, signed URLs and storage keys scoped to the requester.
39-   Look: `jwt.decode(` versus `jwt.verify(`, reads of `X-User-Id` or tenant headers, CORS config treated as the only guard, storage URL generation.
40-   Fail: decode-without-verify feeding authorization: Critical. A trusted client identity header: High.
41:6. A-SEC-6: Password KDF is argon2id, scrypt, bcrypt, or PBKDF2 at cost floors with per-user salts; constant-time comparison on every credential, token, and HMAC; throttling mounted before login, MFA-verify, and reset routes; CSPRNG single-use reset tokens; generic auth errors; no env==dev bypass branch.
42:   Look: hashing calls in `auth/` (`md5`, `sha1`, `createHash` on passwords), `==` on tokens versus `timingSafeEqual`/`compare_digest`, limiter mount line against route registration order, reset token generation.
43-   Fail: fast-hashed or reversible passwords: Critical. Limiter mounted after auth routes, or `==` token comparison: High.
44-7. A-SEC-7: Session and token design: CSPRNG session ids regenerated on privilege change, server-side logout invalidation, Secure/HttpOnly/SameSite cookies; a JWT algorithm allowlist rejecting `alg:none` and RS256-to-HS256 confusion; OAuth is Code plus PKCE with exact-match `redirect_uri` and session-bound state; MFA enforced on the real path.
45-   Look: session config, cookie options, the `algorithms:` option on verify calls, OAuth client config, `startsWith` in redirect validation.
--
68-15. A-SEC-15: The security header set mounts before routes (enforcing CSP without `unsafe-inline`, HSTS, nosniff, frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy) with a presence test; exact-match CORS; production hardened: debug off by default, generic error handlers, no exposed Swagger, introspection, `.git`, or `.env` routes, TRACE off.
69-    Look: helmet or equivalent mount line against route registration, CSP directives, CORS origin logic for reflection or `startsWith`, `DEBUG` defaults, docs and introspection route guards.
70-    Fail: reflected Origin with credentials, or debug defaulting on: High. No enforcing CSP or no header test: Medium.
71:16. A-SEC-16: Resource controls per endpoint class: rate limits on auth, reset, OTP, search, and export; body-size limits; server-enforced max page size; quotas on paid actions; uploads validated by magic bytes with sanitized names stored outside the web root.
72-    Look: limiter configs and which routes mount behind them, `limit`/`page_size` handling, upload middleware options, filename handling.
73-    Fail: no limiter on auth endpoints, or extension-blocklist uploads: High. Unbounded pagination or a missing body cap: Medium.
74-17. A-SEC-17: Supply chain integrity: a committed lockfile installed with `npm ci`, `--immutable`, or `--require-hashes`; digest-pinned base images; actions pinned to 40-char SHAs; ignore-scripts in CI; SCA gating on high or critical with no soft-fail; SBOM from the real graph.
75-    Look: workflow install commands, `uses:` lines carrying `@v` tags, Dockerfile `FROM` lines, `.npmrc`, audit steps with `|| true` or `--audit-level=none`.
76-    Fail: a floating third-party action, or `npm install` in CI despite a lockfile: Medium. A soft-failed SCA gate: High (paper control).
77:18. A-SEC-18: CI/CD access control: least-privilege job tokens, environment protection before prod, no self-approval, protected branches enforced, no `pull_request_target` or `workflow_run` running fork code with secrets in scope.
78:    Look: `permissions:` blocks, `write-all`, `pull_request_target` paired with a checkout of the PR head, environment definitions.
79-    Fail: a poisoned-pipeline pattern with secrets reachable: Critical. A missing permissions block or ungated prod deploy: Medium.
80-19. A-SEC-19: API residue: GraphQL depth, complexity, and cost limits with introspection off in prod; no stale `/v1` or `/internal` mounts with weaker auth; anti-automation on high-value flows; hardened outbound clients (TLS verify on, timeouts, bounded redirects); webhooks verified inbound (HMAC plus replay window) and signed outbound.
81-    Look: GraphQL server options, route mounts for versioned prefixes, webhook receiver signature checks and their comparison operator, outbound client options.
